  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>A solar system on a Brisbane property is generally a positive for buyers, especially in the current environment where electricity costs are a real consideration for owner-occupiers. But solar is also one of the parts of a property sale where buyers and their solicitors ask specific questions, and where vendors who are unprepared can lose credibility or create contract complications. Getting on top of the details before you list makes the process smoother and allows you to present the system confidently as a genuine selling point.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Does solar add measurable value in Brisbane?</h2>
      <p>The short answer is yes, though the premium is not uniform across property types and price brackets. In Brisbane's inner east, a quality solar system on a well-presented family home is consistently treated by buyers as a positive feature, particularly when electricity bills are part of the holding cost conversation. The premium tends to be more visible in the $900,000 to $1.8 million range, where owner-occupiers are buying for the long term and are sensitive to ongoing costs.</p>

      <p>The value attributed to solar is generally related to the system size, its age, the condition of the panels and inverter, and whether battery storage is included. A 10-kilowatt system in good condition with a battery is worth more to a buyer than a 3-kilowatt system installed eight years ago with an aging inverter. Neither adds the same value as the cost of replacement, but a well-documented, functional system is rarely seen as a neutral feature.</p>

      <p>The cases where solar does not add much value tend to involve very old systems with expired warranties, systems with known faults, or situations where the seller has overclaimed the financial benefits in their marketing without documentation to back it up. Buyers who have been burned by inflated solar claims in the past will ask pointed questions, and an agent who cannot answer them clearly creates doubt where there should be confidence.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Ownership, lease, and power purchase agreements</h2>
      <p>The first question buyers and their solicitors ask is whether the solar system is owned outright or subject to a lease or power purchase agreement. This distinction matters legally and financially.</p>

      <p>If you own the system outright, it forms part of the property and passes to the buyer with the title. There is nothing more to do other than ensure the warranty documentation and manuals are available.</p>

      <p>If the system is leased or subject to a power purchase agreement (PPA), it is more complicated. Lease and PPA arrangements are contracts between the homeowner and the solar provider, and they typically have transfer provisions that require the buyer to assume the ongoing payments or allow the contract to be terminated on sale. Some agreements include a balloon payment on termination, which can be thousands of dollars. Buyers and their solicitors will want to see the original contract and understand exactly what they are assuming.</p>

      <p>If your system is under a lease or PPA, get a copy of the contract before you list, confirm the transfer or termination process with the provider, and have that information ready to share with prospective buyers. Surprises at the contract stage are the main source of complications in solar property sales, and most of them are avoidable with preparation.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Transferring a feed-in tariff arrangement</h2>
      <p>Older solar systems in Brisbane may be on grandfathered feed-in tariff rates that are significantly higher than the current standard rate. If your system was installed before around 2012 and you are on one of the original Solar Bonus Scheme rates, this arrangement is registered to you personally and does not automatically transfer to the buyer.</p>

      <p>When your property sells and a new owner is connected to the network, their account will be established at the current standard feed-in tariff rate, not your legacy rate. This is worth being clear about in your marketing, because buyers who assume they will inherit a premium feed-in tariff and later discover they will not may feel misled, even if nothing improper occurred.</p>

      <p>For systems installed more recently, the standard feed-in tariff arrangement follows the property's account rather than the individual, so the buyer should be able to continue receiving feed-in tariff payments after they connect their electricity account. Your retailer can confirm the position for your specific installation.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Inverter age and warranty transferability</h2>
      <p>The inverter is the component buyers and building inspectors focus on most, because it is the part of a solar system most likely to need replacement. Inverters typically last 10 to 15 years, and a good inverter warranty runs for at least five to ten years from installation. If your inverter is approaching the end of its rated life or the warranty has expired, buyers may factor in a replacement cost of $1,000 to $3,000 depending on the system size.</p>

      <p>Check whether your inverter warranty is transferable to a new owner. Most major inverter manufacturers do allow warranty transfer, but it usually requires notification to the manufacturer within a set period after the property changes hands. Having the warranty documents and the manufacturer's transfer process available for buyers is a straightforward step that removes a potential point of friction.</p>

      <p>Panel warranties are usually longer than inverter warranties, often 25 years on performance, and transfer with the property without any specific action required. It is still worth having the documentation available.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Battery storage as a selling point</h2>
      <p>Home battery storage is increasingly common in Brisbane properties, and for the right buyer it is a genuine point of difference. Battery systems allow households to store excess solar generation and use it in the evening rather than exporting it at the feed-in tariff rate, which is particularly relevant as feed-in rates have reduced over recent years.</p>

      <p>When marketing a property with battery storage, the same documentation principles apply: confirm ownership versus lease, provide warranty details, confirm the battery management software version is up to date, and be prepared to explain the system's capacity and typical daily performance in simple terms. Buyers will ask how much it cost to install and how long the warranty runs for. Having accurate answers ready is more effective than enthusiastic but vague claims about savings.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How to present solar in marketing without overclaiming</h2>
      <p>The most credible way to present a solar system in marketing is to state the facts: system size in kilowatts, year of installation, inverter brand and model, battery size if applicable, and whether the system is owned outright. If you have recent electricity bills that demonstrate low costs, you can reference them without speculating about what a future buyer's experience will be.</p>

      <p>Avoid claiming specific dollar savings for the buyer. Their electricity usage, appliance mix, and whether they are home during the day will all affect their experience, and overclaimed savings figures are one of the more reliable ways to create buyer scepticism rather than enthusiasm. Let the system specifications speak for themselves. A well-documented, properly functioning solar system on a well-presented Brisbane home does not need to be oversold.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What to disclose if the system has faults</h2>
      <p>If your solar system has a known fault, whether a panel that is underperforming, an inverter that has had error codes, or a battery that is not cycling correctly, you should disclose this. Queensland's property disclosure framework requires sellers to disclose material facts about the property, and a known defect in a system that is being actively marketed as a feature would be difficult to defend as non-disclosure after the fact.</p>

      <p>In practice, disclosing a fault and adjusting the asking price or offering a credit is a cleaner outcome than a post-settlement dispute. A solar system with a known fault that a buyer discovers during their building and pest inspection, or through a specialist solar inspection, will almost always result in a price renegotiation or a request for a repair credit. Getting ahead of this rather than hoping it will not be noticed protects you and keeps the transaction moving cleanly.</p>

